🧠 OS Concept 1: Race Condition (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Race Condition =
👉 multiple processes access shared data and result depends on execution order

🧠 Real-World Analogy

2 people editing same Google Doc:

Person A writes → 100
Person B writes → 200

Final result depends on:

👉 who saved last

⚙️ Why It Happens

Because of:

No synchronization
Shared memory
⚙️ Example
balance = 1000

Thread1 → balance - 100
Thread2 → balance - 200

Expected:

👉 700

But actual may be:

👉 800 ❌ (wrong)

🔗 Connection

From Day 4:

👉 Critical Section problem

Solution:

👉 Mutex / Semaphore

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is race condition?

👉 When multiple threads access shared data leading to unpredictable results.

🧠 Memory Trick
Race = who finishes first decides result
🧠 OS Concept 2: Starvation & Aging
1️⃣ Starvation

👉 Process never gets CPU

🧠 Real-World Analogy

In queue:

VIP always gets priority
Normal person never gets chance

⚙️ Why It Happens

In:

👉 Priority scheduling

2️⃣ Aging (Solution)

👉 gradually increase priority over time

So eventually:

👉 every process gets CPU

🔗 Connection to Scheduling (Day 3)

Advanced scheduling concept

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is starvation? How to solve it?

👉 Starvation = process waits forever
👉 Solution = Aging

🧠 Memory Trick
Starvation = no chance
Aging = give chance slowly
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Memory Bandwidth vs Latency
1️⃣ Simple Idea

👉 Bandwidth = how much data per second
👉 Latency = delay to access data

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Internet 📶

Bandwidth → speed (MB/s)
Latency → ping delay
⚙️ Example
High bandwidth, high latency → bulk transfer
Low latency → quick response
🔗 Connection to Memory Hierarchy (Day 5)

Cache:

👉 low latency
RAM:

👉 higher latency

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Difference between bandwidth and latency?

👉 Bandwidth = amount
👉 Latency = delay

🧠 Memory Trick
Bandwidth = quantity
Latency = delay
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Multi-core vs Multi-processor

🔥 VERY COMMON CONFUSION

1️⃣ Simple Idea
Multi-core

👉 One CPU with multiple cores

Multi-processor

👉 Multiple CPUs

🧠 Real-World Analogy
Multi-core

One person with multiple hands 🖐️

Multi-processor

Multiple people working 👨‍👨‍👦

⚙️ Difference
Feature	Multi-core	Multi-processor
CPUs	1	many
Cost	low	high
Communication	faster	slower
🔗 Connection to Parallel Processing (Day 10)

Both enable:

👉 parallel execution

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Difference between multi-core and multi-processor?

👉 Multi-core = one CPU many cores
👉 Multi-processor = many CPUs

🧠 Memory Trick
Core = inside CPU
Processor = whole CPU
